<h3>Question 15</h3>
<div><p><p>Write short notes on:</p>
<ol>
<li>Zoom Presentation</li>
<li>Ethical Dilemma</li>
</ol</p></div><div><strong>Answer:</strong><br><style>body .mathjax_wrap{width: 100%;overflow-x: scroll;margin-bottom:10px;}</style><p><strong>Zoom Presentation:</strong></p>
<p>A Zoom presentation refers to a virtual presentation conducted using the Zoom video conferencing platform. It has become increasingly popular for businesses, educational institutions, and individuals to communicate and share information remotely. Here are some key points regarding Zoom presentations:</p>
<ol style="list-style-type:decimal;">
<li><strong>Remote Communication:</strong> Zoom presentations enable presenters to communicate with their audience remotely, eliminating the need for physical presence in the same location.</li>
<li><strong>Features:</strong> Zoom offers various features to enhance presentations, including screen sharing, virtual backgrounds, chat, and annotation tools. These features allow for interactive and engaging presentations.</li>
<li><strong>Flexibility:</strong> Zoom presentations provide flexibility in scheduling and attending meetings, as participants can join from any location with an internet connection. This flexibility is particularly beneficial for global teams or individuals with busy schedules.</li>
<li><strong>Accessibility:</strong> Zoom is accessible across multiple devices, including computers, tablets, and smartphones, making it convenient for participants to join presentations regardless of their location or preferred device.</li>
<li><strong>Security:</strong> While Zoom offers security features to protect meetings from unauthorized access, it&#8217;s essential for presenters to take precautions such as using password protection and managing participant permissions to ensure the security and privacy of their presentations.</li>
<li><strong>Technical Considerations:</strong> Presenters should consider technical aspects such as internet connection stability, audio and video quality, and familiarity with Zoom&#8217;s interface to ensure smooth and successful presentations.</li>
</ol>
<p><strong>Ethical Dilemma:</strong></p>
<p>An ethical dilemma refers to a situation in which a person is faced with a difficult choice between two or more options, each of which entails conflicting ethical principles or values. Here are some key points regarding ethical dilemmas:</p>
<ol style="list-style-type:decimal;">
<li><strong>Conflicting Principles:</strong> Ethical dilemmas arise when individuals are torn between conflicting moral principles, values, or duties. For example, a healthcare professional may face an ethical dilemma when deciding whether to prioritize patient confidentiality or public safety.</li>
<li><strong>Complexity:</strong> Ethical dilemmas often involve complex and nuanced factors that make decision-making challenging. They may involve competing interests, uncertain outcomes, or conflicting obligations.</li>
<li><strong>Personal Values:</strong> Ethical dilemmas are influenced by individuals&#8217; personal values, beliefs, and ethical frameworks. What constitutes the &#8220;right&#8221; or &#8220;wrong&#8221; course of action may vary depending on cultural, religious, or philosophical perspectives.</li>
<li><strong>Decision-Making Process:</strong> Resolving ethical dilemmas requires careful consideration of the potential consequences, weighing the ethical principles at stake, and evaluating alternative courses of action. It may involve seeking guidance from ethical guidelines, consulting with colleagues or mentors, or seeking input from affected parties.</li>
<li><strong>Impact:</strong> The decisions made in response to ethical dilemmas can have significant consequences for individuals, organizations, and society at large. It&#8217;s essential to consider the long-term implications and strive to uphold ethical integrity while navigating challenging situations.</li>
<li><strong>Continuous Reflection:</strong> Ethical dilemmas are inherent in many aspects of professional and personal life. Engaging in continuous reflection, dialogue, and ethical decision-making processes can help individuals develop the skills and resilience needed to address ethical challenges effectively.</li>
</ol>
</div>
</body></html>